body-mixin.summary: The Body mixin of the Fetch API represents the body of the response/request, allowing you to declare what its content type is and how it should be handled.
body-mixin.title: Body

dom-body-arraybuffer.summary: The arrayBuffer() method of the Body mixin takes a Response stream and reads it to completion. It returns a promise that resolves with an ArrayBuffer.
dom-body-arraybuffer.title: Body.arrayBuffer()

dom-body-blob.summary: The blob() method of the Body mixin takes a Response stream and reads it to completion. It returns a promise that resolves with a Blob.
dom-body-blob.title: Body.blob()

dom-body-body.summary: The body read-only property of the Body mixin is a simple getter used to expose a ReadableStream of the body contents.
dom-body-body.title: Body.body

dom-body-bodyused.summary: The bodyUsed read-only property of the Body mixin contains a Boolean that indicates whether the body has been read yet.
dom-body-bodyused.title: Body.bodyUsed

dom-body-formdata.summary: The formData() method of the Body mixin takes a Response stream and reads it to completion. It returns a promise that resolves with a FormData object.
dom-body-formdata.title: Body.formData()

dom-body-json.summary: The json() method of the Body mixin takes a Response stream and reads it to completion. It returns a promise that resolves with the result of parsing the body text as JSON.
dom-body-json.title: Body.json()

dom-body-text.summary: The text() method of the Body mixin takes a Response stream and reads it to completion. It returns a promise that resolves with a USVString object (text). The response is always decoded using UTF-8.
dom-body-text.title: Body.text()

dom-global-fetch.summary: The fetch() method of the WindowOrWorkerGlobalScope mixin starts the process of fetching a resource from the network. This returns a promise that resolves to the Response object representing the response to your request. The promise does not reject on HTTP errors — instead it only rejects only network errors; then handlers must check for HTTP errors.
dom-global-fetch.title: WindowOrWorkerGlobalScope.fetch()

dom-headers.summary: The Headers() constructor creates a new Headers object.
dom-headers.title: Headers()

dom-headers-append.summary: The append() method of the Headers interface appends a new value onto an existing header inside a Headers object, or adds the header if it does not already exist.
dom-headers-append.title: Headers.append()

dom-headers-delete.summary: The delete() method of the Headers interface deletes a header from the current Headers object.
dom-headers-delete.title: Headers.delete()

dom-headers-get.summary: The get() method of the Headers interface returns a byte string of all the values of a header within a Headers object with a given name. If the requested header doesn't exist in the Headers object, it returns null.

firefox.notes: Prior to Firefox 52, get() only returned the first value in the specified header, with getAll() returning all values. From 52 onwards, get() now returns all values and getAll() has been deleted.

dom-headers-get.title: Headers.get()

dom-headers-get.summary: The get() method of the Headers interface returns a byte string of all the values of a header within a Headers object with a given name. If the requested header doesn't exist in the Headers object, it returns null.
dom-headers-get.title: Headers.get()

dom-headers-set.summary: The set() method of the Headers interface sets a new value for an existing header inside a Headers object, or adds the header if it does not already exist.
dom-headers-set.title: Headers.set()

dom-request.summary: The Request() constructor creates a new Request object.

chrome.notes: Some default values for the init parameter changed in Chrome 47. See the Properties section for details.

chrome_android.notes: Some default values for the init parameter changed in Chrome 47. See the Properties section for details.

samsunginternet_android.notes: Some default values for the init parameter changed in Samsung Internet 5.0. See the Properties section for details.

webview_android.notes: Some default values for the init parameter changed in Chrome 47. See the Properties section for details.

dom-request.title: Request()

dom-request-cache.summary: The cache read-only property of the Request interface contains the cache mode of the request. It controls how the request will interact with the browser's HTTP cache.
dom-request-cache.title: Request.cache

dom-request-clone.summary: The clone() method of the Request interface creates a copy of the current Request object.
dom-request-clone.title: Request.clone()

dom-request-credentials.summary: The credentials read-only property of the Request interface indicates whether the user agent should send cookies from the other domain in the case of cross-origin requests. This is similar to XHR’s withCredentials flag, but with three available values (instead of two):
dom-request-credentials.title: Request.credentials

dom-request-destination.summary: The destination read-only property of the Request interface returns a string describing the type of content being requested.
dom-request-destination.title: Request.destination

dom-request-headers.summary: The headers read-only property of the Request interface contains the Headers object associated with the request.
dom-request-headers.title: Request.headers

dom-request-integrity.summary: The integrity read-only property of the Request interface contains the subresource integrity value of the request.
dom-request-integrity.title: Request.integrity

dom-request-method.summary: The method read-only property of the Request interface contains the request's method (GET, POST, etc.)
dom-request-method.title: Request.method

dom-request-mode.summary: The mode read-only property of the Request interface contains the mode of the request (e.g., cors, no-cors, same-origin, or navigate.) This is used to determine if cross-origin requests lead to valid responses, and which properties of the response are readable.
dom-request-mode.title: Request.mode

dom-request-redirect.summary: The redirect read-only property of the Request interface contains the mode for how redirects are handled.
dom-request-redirect.title: Request.redirect

dom-request-referrer.summary: The referrer read-only property of the Request interface is set by the user agent to be the referrer of the Request. (e.g., client, no-referrer, or a URL.)
dom-request-referrer.title: Request.referrer

dom-request-referrerpolicy.summary: The referrerPolicy read-only property of the Request interface returns the referrer policy, which governs what referrer information, sent in the Referer header, should be included with the request.
dom-request-referrerpolicy.title: Request.referrerPolicy

dom-request-url.summary: The url read-only property of the Request interface contains the URL of the request.
dom-request-url.title: Request.url

dom-response.summary: The Response() constructor creates a new Response object.
dom-response.title: Response()

dom-response-clone.summary: The clone() method of the Response interface creates a clone of a response object, identical in every way, but stored in a different variable.
dom-response-clone.title: Response.clone()

dom-response-error.summary: The error() method of the Response interface returns a new Response object associated with a network error.
dom-response-error.title: Response.error()

dom-response-headers.summary: The headers read-only property of the Response interface contains the Headers object associated with the response.
dom-response-headers.title: Response.headers

dom-response-ok.summary: The ok read-only property of the Response interface contains a Boolean stating whether the response was successful (status in the range 200-299) or not.
dom-response-ok.title: Response.ok

dom-response-redirect.summary: The redirect() method of the Response interface returns a Response resulting in a redirect to the specified URL.
dom-response-redirect.title: Response.redirect()

dom-response-redirected.summary: The read-only redirected property of the Response interface indicates whether or not the response is the result of a request you made which was redirected.
dom-response-redirected.title: Response.redirected

dom-response-status.summary: The status read-only property of the Response interface contains the status code of the response (e.g., 200 for a success).
dom-response-status.title: Response.status

dom-response-statustext.summary: The statusText read-only property of the Response interface contains the status message corresponding to the status code (e.g., OK for 200).
dom-response-statustext.title: Response.statusText

dom-response-type.summary: The type read-only property of the Response interface contains the type of the response. It can be one of the following:
dom-response-type.title: Response.type

dom-response-url.summary: The url read-only property of the Response interface contains the URL of the response. The value of the url property will be the final URL obtained after any redirects.
dom-response-url.title: Response.url

fetch-method.summary: The fetch() method of the WindowOrWorkerGlobalScope mixin starts the process of fetching a resource from the network. This returns a promise that resolves to the Response object representing the response to your request. The promise does not reject on HTTP errors — instead it only rejects only network errors; then handlers must check for HTTP errors.
fetch-method.title: WindowOrWorkerGlobalScope.fetch()

headers-class.summary: The Headers interface of the Fetch API allows you to perform various actions on HTTP request and response headers. These actions include retrieving, setting, adding to, and removing. A Headers object has an associated header list, which is initially empty and consists of zero or more name and value pairs.  You can add to this using methods like append() (see Examples.) In all methods of this interface, header names are matched by case-insensitive byte sequence.
headers-class.title: Headers

http-access-control-allow-credentials.summary: The Access-Control-Allow-Credentials response header tells browsers whether to expose the response to frontend JavaScript code when the request's credentials mode (Request.credentials) is "include".
http-access-control-allow-credentials.title: Access-Control-Allow-Credentials

http-access-control-allow-headers.summary: The Access-Control-Allow-Headers response header is used in response to a preflight request which includes the Access-Control-Request-Headers to indicate which HTTP headers can be used during the actual request.
http-access-control-allow-headers.title: Access-Control-Allow-Headers

http-access-control-allow-methods.summary: The Access-Control-Allow-Methods response header specifies the method or methods allowed when accessing the resource in response to a preflight request.
http-access-control-allow-methods.title: Access-Control-Allow-Methods

http-access-control-allow-origin.summary: The Access-Control-Allow-Origin response header indicates whether the response can be shared with requesting code from the given origin.
http-access-control-allow-origin.title: Access-Control-Allow-Origin

http-access-control-expose-headers.summary: The Access-Control-Expose-Headers response header indicates which headers can be exposed as part of the response by listing their names.
http-access-control-expose-headers.title: Access-Control-Expose-Headers

http-access-control-max-age.summary: The Access-Control-Max-Age response header indicates how long the results of a preflight request (that is the information contained in the Access-Control-Allow-Methods and Access-Control-Allow-Headers headers) can be cached.
http-access-control-max-age.title: Access-Control-Max-Age

http-access-control-request-headers.summary: The Access-Control-Request-Headers request header is used when issuing a preflight request to let the server know which HTTP headers will be used when the actual request is made.
http-access-control-request-headers.title: Access-Control-Request-Headers

http-access-control-request-method.summary: The Access-Control-Request-Method request header is used when issuing a preflight request to let the server know which HTTP method will be used when the actual request is made. This header is necessary as the preflight request is always an OPTIONS and doesn't use the same method as the actual request.
http-access-control-request-method.title: Access-Control-Request-Method

origin-header.summary: The Origin request header indicates where a fetch originates from. It doesn't include any path information, but only the server name. It is sent with CORS requests, as well as with POST requests. It is similar to the Referer header, but, unlike this header, it doesn't disclose the whole path.

firefox.notes: Sent with non-CORS requests since Fx59, unless they are GET or HEAD.
Not sent with POST requests until Firefox 58, see bug 446344.

firefox_android.notes: Sent with non-CORS requests since Fx59, unless they are GET or HEAD.
Not sent with POST requests until Firefox 58, see bug 446344.

origin-header.title: Origin

request-class.summary: The Request interface of the Fetch API represents a resource request.
request-class.title: Request

requestdestination.summary: The RequestDestination enumerated type contains the permitted values for a request's destination. These string values indicate potential types of content that a request may try to retrieve.
requestdestination.title: RequestDestination

response-class.summary: The Response interface of the Fetch API represents the response to a request.
response-class.title: Response

x-content-type-options-header.summary: The X-Content-Type-Options response HTTP header is a marker used by the server to indicate that the MIME types advertised in the Content-Type headers should not be changed and be followed. This allows to opt-out of MIME type sniffing, or, in other words, it is a way to say that the webmasters knew what they were doing.
x-content-type-options-header.title: X-Content-Type-Options
